You either need to keep a separate ArrayList of C1 and C2 instances, or you have to cast them to their respective types to use the methods of the subtypes. Something like:

    A.get(x).method_of_C0();
    ((C1)A.get(0)).method_of_C1();
    ((C2)A.get(1)).method_of_C2();

You might also use the **instanceof** keyword to check that an element is actually an instance of a particular subtype before you do the casting, otherwise you&#39;ll get a ClassCastException.

But note that this has a pretty bad code smell, so keeping track of each subtype as you need them is probably the way to go.

The problem here is that you are not declaring an object type when instantiating a new Instance of the ArrayList.  
Here is the easiest way to solve your problem:

    ArrayList&lt;C0&gt; A = new ArrayList&lt;C0&gt;();
    A.add( new C1() );
    A.add( new C2() );

Now the following lines of code should work. As long as C1 and C2 are subclasses of C0.

    A.get(0).method_C1();
    A.get(1).method_C2();

